50|$|His son, Alfred Frederick Bird, {{continued}} {{the work of}} his father. Bird junior went on to invent egg substitute powder in 1890, <b>blancmange</b> <b>powder</b> and jelly powder.|$|E
50|$|After he {{discovered}} his custard was popular, Bird formed Alfred Bird and Sons Ltd. in Birmingham. By 1843, {{the company was}} also making the newly invented baking powder and, by 1844, was promoting custard powder nationally. By 1895, the company was producing <b>blancmange</b> <b>powder,</b> jelly powder, and egg substitute. In World War I, Bird's Custard was supplied to the British armed forces.|$|E

